nts and have anti-inflammatory properties, making them useful in treating conditions such as fever and respiratory problems. In addition to its leaves, the plant's rhizome is also used in traditional medicine to treat various health conditions. The plant's leaves are also used to treat skin conditions and wounds due to their antiseptic properties. The exact composition and uses of Trichomanes indicum's medicinal parts may vary depending on the region and traditional practices.", "intro": "Trichomanes indicum, also known as Indian maidenhair fern, is a species of vascular plant that belongs to the family Hymenophyllaceae. It has been traditionally used in Ayurvedic medicine to treat various health issues, including fever, rheumatism, and digestive problems, due to its anti-inflammatory, antipyretic, and antimicrobial properties. The bioactive constituents of Trichomanes indicum include flavonoids, alkaloids, and glycosides, which are responsible for its medicinal effects. In herbal medicine, Trichomanes indicum is commonly prepared as a decoction or powder, and it is also used in the form of an infusion to treat a range of health conditions."}